                      <locus target="#121v" facs="124"/> in pen: Note of later ownership: <q>“This bible belongs to Deacon Sǝyum.”</q>
                      </desc>
                      </item>
                      <item xml:id="e2">
                      <desc>
                      words of text are written interlinearly (<locus target="#43v #55v #65r #83v" facs="046 058 067 086"/>, etc.);
                      and lines of text are written interlinearly (<locus target="#16r #23v #50r #51v #63v" facs="018 026 052 054 066"/>, etc.);
                      and in another case interlinearly where the symbol (┬) is used (<locus target="#62v" facs="065"/>, line 19);
                      erasure markings are visible (<locus target="#60v #78r #102r #103r" facs="063 080 104 105"/>);
                      text has been removed (e.g., <locus target="#31r #39r #43r #90r" facs="033 041 045 092"/>)
                      </desc>
                      </item>
                      <item xml:id="e3">
                        <desc>
                          The scribe regularly has to complete a line of text on another line. Much of the problem is
                          addressed through the selection of an appropriate aspect ratio for the codex combined with an appropriate script size. But, where
                          the line of text is still too long, the scribe completes the line of text above or below the end of the line (throughout)
                        </desc>
                      </item>

